	   <tr><td colspan=2>I say that if you want to give away an item, you might as well make the newbie work for it.&nbsp;&nbsp;For instance, say you wanted to give away one of these swords to a newbie in the Qeynos Hills area.  Have the newbie do a small quest for you.  For instance, I will give you a fine weapon if you are a paladin giving the quest: <br><br>"I have heard reports of numerous undead lurking in this area. These walking dead are in direct defiance to my lord, Mithanael Marr, and must be dealt with.  Therefore, I require proof that you serve my cause.  If you return to me the rotting flesh of a sailor (zombie sailors, Erud's Crossing), bones putrid with stench (putrid skeletons, Qeynos Hills), and bones cold from frost, I will give you a weapon worthy of your prowess."<br><br>You can ham it up however you like, but get some roleplaying out of it too.  It makes the game so much more fun when you're waiting forever for Hadden to spawn so you can get that Fishbone Earring you've been craving.<br><br>Personally, I'd ask for various instrument parts, being a bard.  Like, 4 silk cords for instrument strings, an appropriate skin for drum heads, bone chips for pegs, a flute mouthpiece, and an unfinished trumpet, or something of the sort.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
