<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99272375875833></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99272375875833><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=6042&mid=99272375875833>RE: Can't Wait</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=6042&mid=99272375875833#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2087><span id=Sage>Novenlestmeiche</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>42 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Jun 16th 4:35 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There are 2 ways to calculate the weapon ratio of any weapon.&nbsp;&nbsp;One is to devide the damage by the delay, doing so you often get a number below 1, such as the way your used to seing it.  This means that a weapon with a ratio of 1 is a good weapon and the higher the number the beter.  Where as a simpler way to do so in game (I rarely keep a calculator or pen/paper on hand) is to devide the delay by the damage, which usually results in a whole number.  In this case you are looking for the weapon with the lowest number.  Lower is better.<br><br>So to recap:<br>Damage\Delay= (higher number is better)<br>Delay\Damage= (Lower number is better)<br>&nbsp;<br>Novenlestmeiche-55-Wood Elf Druid-Ayonae<br>Reezon-48-halfling Rogue-Ayonae<br>Gourgone-25-Troll Warrior</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
